node.text:
The “scoop marks” are widely present at the oldest megalithic sites scattered throughout the world.
_

From Egypt to South America, these marks can be seen at Macchu Picchu, Ollantaytambo, the Aswan Quarry, the three main pyramids at Giza on the casing stones and granite blocks scattered in their vicinity, but also Stonehenge and other megalithic sites in England.
_

The process that was used to craft these stones and that left the scoop marks on them is matter of debate and a still unexplained topic.
_

The main hypothesis laid out by Egyptologists is that the marks at the Aswan Quarry were left as a result of pounding the granite with diorite balls.
_

Not only this process would be incredibly slow, but it also wouldn’t have left symmetrical and even marks.
_

The tight space flanking the unfinished obelisk would’ve left no maneuvering space to perform such technique.
_

Moreover, the marks go from the side of the obelisk but they also stretch under it (Pic.2), making it practically impossible to achieve by pounding.
_

The marks are also present on top of the obelisk itself (Pic.3).
_

Diorite is also almost the same hardness than granite on the Mohs Scale, making the alleged process extremely hard to be performed at this level.
_

The sophistication at Aswan and throughout ancient Egyptian megalithic sites is such that it’s quite naive to imagine them bashing against granite with diorite balls.
_

Even the Wikipedia page reads as follows: “Modern Egyptian suggests the use of diorite balls as carving tools for granite, at Aswan; a frequently repeated but scientifically unproven method”.
_

Technique aside, the real enigma is how and why the civilizations of England and South America knew this exact process. 
_

Going back in time trying to figure out how old this process might be things get even more baffling, as the scoop marks can be spotted at 12.000 years old Gobekli Tepe in Turkey on top of the famous T-shaped pillars (pic.4).

Uruk: The First City Built By King Gilgamesh 4,500 Years Aug.
Uruk Prophecy Found In The Ancient Library Of A Magician With Divine Powers.  Uruk Prophecy Found In The Ancient Library Of A Magician With Divine Powers. In 1969, members of the German Warka expedition discovered an ancient damaged clay tablet in Uruk, the first city built by Gilgamesh about 4,000 years ago.  Examination of this interesting ancient artifact revealed it contained what today is known as the Uruk Prophecy. Later, scientists unearthed several other old clay tablets. These Sumerian inscriptions were once part of an ancient library belonging to Anu-iksur, a magician who was said to have had divine powers. Uruk Prophecy Found In The Ancient Library Of A Magician With Divine Powers. Although badly broken, scientists managed to read and translate the inscriptions carved on the clay tablet that contained the Uruk prophecy. It was a very interesting text describing the arrival of an unjust king who will make life miserable for people and bring terror on the whole world. According to legends, the ancient Sumerian city of Uruk was built by Gilgamesh, a demigod of superhuman strength. The city of Uruk was originally built for Anu, the father of the gods and his daughter, Inanna, the goddess of love and war.  Gilgamesh also irrigated the fields, dug wells, and made orchards. Ancient Sumerians and Babylonians constantly observed the night skies and were very skilled astronomers. Two-sided stela of pluriform Thoth. A.D. 1st–2nd century, probably Roman Period
Limestone. Dimensions: 6 1/2 x 5 9/16 x 1 3/16 in. (16.5 x 14.2 x 3 cm). On view at The Met Fifth Avenue in Gallery 137. 
Thoth appears three times, from left to right: assimilated with the moon god Khonsu-Harpokrates, in baboon form, and as an ibis-headed crowned figure. 
The last wears an elaborate mythological kilt like those seen on representations of Roman Period pharaohs at Dendara. Three small panels on the kilt illustrate, from top: a griffin-type form that presumably represents the god Nemesis, an eagle(?), and a seated baboon.

node.text:
The Hoysaleswara temple, dedicated to Lord Shiva is a 12th CE Hindu temple built by King Vishnuvardhana. It is the largest monument in Halebidu, a town in the state of Karnataka, India and the former capital of the Hoysala Empire. It took about 40 years (1121 CE-1160 CE) of painstaking sculpting before it took the form that we see today. It’s real beauty lies in the sculptures that run along the outer wall and in its doorways.

Each of these sculptures portray a story from Hindu religious texts. The work is so intricate that you need to have a keen eye, lots of time at hand and oodles of patience just to cover a few feet of these sculptures. That is how much work that has gone into this articulate monument from a glorious era. Even though the temple was sacked and damaged twice by Muslim armies of Malik Kafur, the regional general of the Delhi Sultanate in the 14th CE, the Hoysaleswara temple still stands tall to this day.

When you touch these sculptures, you cannot stop yourself imagining how on earth the sculptors of 900 years ago managed such high levels of finish, polish and minute detailed carving without any of the modern machinery or some of the latest tools. The Hoysaleswara temple holds a spectacular wealth of soapstone sculptures of all shapes and sizes. Soapstone is a delicate material but lends itself well to the creation of detailed fine carvings.

It is relatively soft and even-textured, ranges from deep pink to white and looks similar to marble when polished. Its characteristics are exploited to the utmost here: row upon row of intertwined animals, dancers, mythical monsters and Hindu divinities. No two the same, line every surface and appear surreal and glorious in the temple's half-light. The Hoysala architecture is a happy blend of the Nagara style of North India and the Dravidian style of the South India.

A remarkable feature of this temple is that it has been built on star-shaped platform. The platform themself is embellished with friezes of contemporary creatures-horses, elephants and swans as well as processions of dancing maidens and tribute bearers. The Hoysaleswara temple is truly magnificent in every way.

Haamong-a-Maui ("the burden of the god Maui"), also known as the Tonga Gate is a megalithic arch, a stone trilithon, in the northern Tongatapu Island (Kingdom of Tonga) of the southwest Pacific Ocean, a part of Polynesia. It is the only megalithic arch in the South Pacific. It consists of three limestone coral slabs, each about 6 meters long, and the weight of each visible piece of vertical stone is about 30-40 tons. The top of the vertical blocks contains a deep groove that serves to join the horizontal lintel, with a small gap of about 5 cm. The joined elements are carefully fitted to each other, but not perfect. According to local legends, Haamonga was created by the god Maui from stones he brought from Wallis Island, as the stones would have been too enormous for mortals to handle. The word "haamonga" means "a stick with weights on both ends, carried over the shoulder." The first two photographs are from 1880-1889.  Haʻamonga ʻa Maui ("The Burden of Maui") is a stone trilithon located in Tonga, on the eastern part of the island of Tongatapu, in the village of Niutōua, in Heketā. It was built in the 13th century by King Tuʻitātui in honor of his two sons. The monument is sometimes called the "Stonehenge of the Pacific".
